{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cf72c2dd-2bd6-4a72-804b-158e5a65028d","content":"Here's my analysis of the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Deep Import Chain (level1 → level2 → level3)\n\nThe project imports `level1.props`, which imports `level2.props`, which imports `level3.props`. Each nested import requires MSBuild to locate, open, parse, and evaluate a separate file **during the evaluation phase**. Deep chains increase I/O and add latency linearly. Flatten these into a single file or reduce nesting where possible.\n\n## 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern\n\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n\nThe `**\\*.*` glob recursively scans the entire directory tree during evaluation. It will traverse `.git/`, `node_modules/`, and any other large subtree not explicitly excluded. Use more targeted patterns (e.g., `**\\*.cs`) or add entries to `DefaultItemExcludes` to restrict scanning.\n\n## 3. File I/O via Property Function During Evaluation\n\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n\nThis reads a file from disk **during project evaluation**, not during the execution phase. Evaluation is meant to be fast and deterministic; disk I/O here blocks the evaluator and cannot be parallelized or cached. Move file reads to a target that runs during execution instead:\n\n```xml\n<Target Name=\"ReadBuildNotes\" BeforeTargets=\"Build\">\n  <ReadLinesFromFile File=\"build-notes.txt\">\n    <Output TaskParameter=\"Lines\" ItemName=\"BuildNotesLines\"/>\n  </ReadLinesFromFile>\n</Target>\n```\n\n## Evaluation vs. Execution Phase\n\nMSBuild's **evaluation phase** processes imports, property groups, item groups, and globs to build the project model. It runs synchronously and must complete before any target executes. Expensive operations here (deep imports, broad globs, property-function I/O) directly increase IDE load times and restore/build startup. The **execution phase** (targets/tasks) runs later and supports parallelism and incrementality—heavy work belongs there.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"55def0fc-2b83-4702-8c5a-bb6941d69c69","outputTokens":521,"requestId":"5C01:74DAE:1E6E07E:224CA88:6A07CA77"},"id":"e1ddc0fe-19c1-4835-ad31-a4475f44ef07","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:38:11.656Z","parentId":"da860b7d-2270-4bd4-adb8-e43b87c1459f"}
